<DOC><DOCNO> AP880502-0304 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1934EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-InsiderTradingCharge     05-02 0204</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Insider Trading Charge,0210</SECOND><HEAD>Executive Recruiter Accused of Insider Trading</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Securities and Exchange Commission onMonday accused a Massachusetts man of violating insider tradingregulations by making stock profits based on information he learnedin his job as head of a corporate recruiting firm.   The SEC civil complaint accused Michael O. Ingoldsby of making$14,000 in profit in trading shares of stock in ArtelCommunications Corp., a fiber optics company with headquarters inHudson, Mass.   The SEC charged that Ingoldsby, the head of an executive searchfirm located in Wellesley, Mass., was hired by Artel in September1986 to find a new chief executive for the company.   Ingoldsby allegedly purchased 23,500 shares of Artel stock afterlearning that Robert L. Bowman, an executive he had recruited tohead Artel, was about to accept the top post at the company.   The SEC complaint, which was filed in federal court in Boston,seeks an injunction barring Ingoldsby from violatinginsider-trading regulations in the future and seeks fines equal tothe $14,000 he allegedly made in profit in trading Artel stock.   Ingoldsby, the head of Michael O. Ingoldsby Associations Inc.,did not return phone calls asking for comment on the SEC charges.</TEXT></DOC>